  })}
  initialNumToRender={20}
  maxToRenderPerBatch={10}
  windowSize={10}
  removeClippedSubviews={true}
  renderItem={memoizedItemRenderer}
/>
```

## Core Purpose
Native Modules enable access to platform-specific APIs and performance-critical operations not available in JavaScript, creating a bridge between JS and native iOS/Android code.

## When to Use
**Ideal scenarios:**
- Bluetooth/Peripheral communication
- Biometric authentication
- Advanced camera controls
- Custom hardware integration
- CPU-intensive calculations

**When NOT to use:**
- Simple UI operations
- Basic storage needs
- Network requests (use fetch/axios)
- When JS performance is sufficient

## Performance Considerations
**Bridge Overhead:** Each async call crosses the bridge with serialization cost. Batch operations when possible.

**Threading Model:**
- Native modules run on main thread by default
- Use background threads for heavy computations
- JS thread must never block

**Memory Management:**
- Clean up native resources in dealloc
- Avoid memory leaks across bridge
- Use proper promise/reject patterns

## Code Example
```java
// Android native module
@ReactMethod
public Promise performHeavyComputation(Promise promise) {
  new Thread(() -> {
    try {
      String result = heavyCalculation();
      promise.resolve(result);
    } catch (Exception e) {
      promise.reject("ERROR", e.getMessage());
    }
  }).start();
}
```

## Real-World Applications
- **Airbnb:** Custom camera filters
- **Discord:** Voice chat integration
- **Uber:** Location services optimization
- **Spotify:** Audio processing modules

## Concept Overview
Optimizing large-scale React Native lists requires a multi-faceted approach addressing JavaScript execution efficiency, layout calculation optimization, and animation performance management.

## Implementation Details
- **FlatList Optimization**: Configure `getItemLayout` for predictable item heights, enable `removeClippedSubviews` for memory efficiency, and tune `maxToRenderPerBatch` for balanced rendering
- **Hermes Engine Benefits**: Leverage bytecode precompilation for faster startup times, reduced memory footprint for better performance on low-end devices, and optimized JavaScript execution
- **Reanimated 2 Integration**: Utilize `useSharedValue` for state management and `useAnimatedStyle` for UI-thread animations, preventing main thread blocking
- **Memoization Strategy**: Apply `React.memo` to prevent unnecessary re-renders and `useCallback` for stable function references

## Code Example
```javascript
const OptimizedListItem = React.memo(({ item, sharedValue }) => {
  const animatedStyle = useAnimatedStyle(() => ({
    transform: [{ scale: sharedValue.value }]
  }));

  return (
    <Animated.View style={[styles.item, animatedStyle]}>
      <Text>{item.title}</Text>
    </Animated.View>
  );
});

const renderItem = useCallback(({ item }) => (
  <OptimizedListItem item={item} sharedValue={scaleShared} />
), []);

return (
  <FlatList
    data={largeDataSet}
    renderItem={renderItem}
    getItemLayout={(data, index) => ({
      length: ITEM_HEIGHT,
      offset: ITEM_HEIGHT * index,
      index,
    })}
    removeClippedSubviews
    maxToRenderPerBatch={10}
    windowSize={10}
  />
);
```
